  :prose
"Chapter 4 sketched a toy solar system with arbitrary numbers. This
appendix gives you REAL numbers — the masses, distances, and initial
velocities of the sun and eight planets in units suitable for
`phys/nbody`. Drop them in, tune the time-step, and you have a
working solar-system simulation that reproduces Kepler's laws to
several digits.

Then a Q&A section with the sorts of questions kids ask when they
see the sim running.

---

## I.1 The units

Astronomers use several unit systems. We use the AU-YEAR-SOLAR-MASS
system, in which:

- Length: 1 AU (astronomical unit) = mean Earth-sun distance ~150M km
- Time: 1 year = ~365.25 days
- Mass: 1 solar mass = ~2e30 kg
- Gravitational constant G = 4*pi^2 (in these units, for orbits
  around 1 solar mass at 1 AU)

This makes Kepler's third law dead simple: `T^2 = a^3` for orbits
around the sun, with T in years and a in AU.

## I.2 The bodies

| Body      | Mass (solar) | Semi-major axis (AU) | Orbital period (yr) | Initial vel (AU/yr) |
|-----------|-------------:|---------------------:|--------------------:|--------------------:|
| Sun       | 1.0          | 0                    | -                   | 0                   |
| Mercury   | 1.66e-7      | 0.387                | 0.241               | 10.07               |
| Venus     | 2.45e-6      | 0.723                | 0.615               | 7.38                |
| Earth     | 3.00e-6      | 1.000                | 1.000               | 6.28                |
| Mars      | 3.23e-7      | 1.524                | 1.881               | 5.09                |
| Jupiter   | 9.55e-4      | 5.204                | 11.86               | 2.75                |
| Saturn    | 2.86e-4      | 9.583                | 29.46               | 2.03                |
| Uranus    | 4.37e-5      | 19.19                | 84.01               | 1.43                |
| Neptune   | 5.15e-5      | 30.07                | 164.8               | 1.14                |

Initial velocities assume circular orbits at aphelion. Real orbits
are slightly elliptical; for research use, feed real ephemeris data.

## I.3 The kit

```scheme
(define solar-system
  '((sun     1.0      (0 0)     (0 0))
    (mercury 1.66e-7  (0.387 0) (0 10.07))
    (venus   2.45e-6  (0.723 0) (0  7.38))
    (earth   3.00e-6  (1.000 0) (0  6.28))
    (mars    3.23e-7  (1.524 0) (0  5.09))
    (jupiter 9.55e-4  (5.204 0) (0  2.75))
    (saturn  2.86e-4  (9.583 0) (0  2.03))
    (uranus  4.37e-5  (19.19 0) (0  1.43))
    (neptune 5.15e-5  (30.07 0) (0  1.14))))

(define (setup-solar-system)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/integrator! 'verlet)         ;; symplectic, essential for orbits
  (define G-effective (* 4 (* 3.14159 3.14159)))
  (for-each
    (lambda (body)
      (let* ((name (car body))
             (mass (cadr body))
             (pos  (caddr body))
             (vel  (cadddr body))
             (e    (world/spawn name (car pos) (cadr pos))))
        (entity/mass!    e mass)
        (entity/set-vel! e (car vel) (cadr vel))))
    solar-system)
  ;; Install all-pairs mutual gravity
  (let ((entities (map (lambda (b) (world/find (car b))) solar-system)))
    (for-each
      (lambda (a)
        (for-each
          (lambda (b)
            (when (not (eq? a b))
              (world/attract! a b G-effective)))
          entities))
      entities)))

(setup-solar-system)
```

Time-step: `1/1000` of a year is small enough for stable outer-planet
orbits. `1/10000` for high accuracy over 100 years.

```scheme
(world/dt! (/ 1.0 1000))
(on-frame (lambda (t) (world/step)))
```

At 60 fps, 1000 steps per year = 16.7 years per second of wall time.
The inner planets (Mercury, Earth) whirl fast; Neptune's 164-year
orbit takes ~10 seconds of wall-clock time to complete.

## I.4 Verifying Kepler

Kepler's laws:

- **First**: orbits are ellipses with the sun at one focus.
- **Second**: equal areas swept in equal times.
- **Third**: `T^2 = a^3` in these units.

To verify the third law:

```scheme
(define (measure-period name expected)
  (let ((body (world/find name))
        (start-pos (entity/pos (world/find name))))
    ;; Wait for the body to return to its starting angle.
    (let loop ((t 0))
      (world/step)
      (let ((now (entity/pos body)))
        (if (and (> t (/ expected 4))     ;; wait at least a quarter orbit
                 (angular-diff (angle-of now) (angle-of start-pos)) < 0.01)
            (list name 'period-measured (* t (world/dt))))))
      (loop (+ t 1)))))

(measure-period 'earth 1.0)     ;; should be ~1.000
(measure-period 'jupiter 11.86) ;; should be ~11.86
```

## I.5 The Voyager slingshot

A classic use of solar-system sim. Fire a probe from Earth. Time it
to pass Jupiter closely. Watch it fling out into the outer solar
system, exchanging some of Jupiter's orbital energy for its own.

```scheme
;; A tiny mass at Earth's orbit, initial velocity slightly outward
(define voyager
  (let ((v (world/spawn 'voyager 1.02 0)))
    (entity/mass! v 1e-15)
    (entity/set-vel! v 0.5 6.9)       ;; slightly faster than Earth, angled out
    (world/attract! v (world/find 'sun) (* 4 (* 3.14159 3.14159)))
    (world/attract! v (world/find 'jupiter) (* 4 (* 3.14159 3.14159)))
    v))
```

Watch: the probe curves outward on a spiral. When it passes near
Jupiter, its velocity changes dramatically. Depending on timing, it
can be flung out into the outer system or captured into a Jovian
orbit.

## I.6 The Q&A

**Q: Why doesn't Mercury spiral into the sun?**
Because gravity's radial pull is balanced by Mercury's tangential
velocity's angular-momentum requirement. Mercury falls TOWARD the
sun, but also moves sideways fast enough that it always misses.
That's what an orbit IS.

**Q: What if I made Jupiter twice as massive?**
Try it. Earth's orbit gets perturbed noticeably. Mars might be
destabilized after enough time. The inner planets are all in
delicate resonance with Jupiter's gravity — change Jupiter and you
change the whole inner-system stability.

**Q: What if I removed the sun?**
The planets fly off in straight lines (their tangential velocities
at the moment of removal). Some may weakly gravitationally interact
with each other and change slightly, but mostly they escape.

**Q: Are the orbits really flat?**
Approximately. Real orbits are within a few degrees of a common
plane (the ecliptic). Our 2D sim treats everything as coplanar; a
3D sim would show real tilts.

**Q: What about the moon?**
Add it: mass 3.7e-8, initial position (1.003, 0) — Earth's position
plus lunar distance, initial velocity Earth's velocity plus lunar
orbital velocity ~2.06 AU/year in the perpendicular direction.

```scheme
(define moon
  (let ((m (world/spawn 'moon 1.003 0)))
    (entity/mass! m 3.7e-8)
    (entity/set-vel! m 0 (+ 6.28 2.06))
    ...))
```

The moon then orbits Earth in ~1 month while both orbit the sun.

**Q: Is Pluto still there?**
Add it: mass 6.6e-9, semi-major axis 39.48 AU, initial velocity 0.99
AU/year, in a noticeably eccentric orbit.

**Q: What about asteroids?**
Add a Trojan asteroid at Earth's L4 point: mass 1e-14, position
Earth-relative +60 degrees in orbit. It should stay there (roughly).

**Q: What if two planets collide?**
Numerically, they'd pass through each other. Add
`(world/on-collision! ...)` to merge them (conserving momentum).

## I.7 Precession

Mercury's orbit precesses — the ellipse's major axis slowly rotates.
Newtonian gravity predicts some precession; the actual observed
precession is a tiny bit more, and Einstein's general relativity
explains the difference. Watch Mercury for many orbits; you'll see
the precession as a slow rotation of the elliptical trace.

## I.8 Escape velocity

At Earth's orbit, escape velocity from the sun is ~sqrt(2) times
Earth's orbital velocity, or ~8.89 AU/year. Try firing a body at
various speeds from (1, 0):

```scheme
(define escapees
  (map (lambda (v)
         (let ((e (world/spawn (string->symbol
                                 (string-append \"escape-\" (number->string v)))
                               1.0 0)))
           (entity/mass! e 1e-15)
           (entity/set-vel! e 0 v)
           (world/attract! e (world/find 'sun) (* 4 (* 3.14159 3.14159)))
           e))
       '(6.28 7.0 8.0 8.89 9.5 10.0)))
```

The first three loop back. 8.89 barely escapes on a parabolic
trajectory. 9.5 and 10 escape on hyperbolas.

## I.9 The takeaway

Real solar-system simulation is just `phys/nbody` with realistic
masses and velocities. Chapter 4's toy sim scales up to Voyager
missions with only unit corrections. This kit is calibrated; drop it
in and go.

